06317nam a22008175i 9780774860727DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748607277 a10.59962/97807748607272doi  a(DE-B1597)661183  a(OCoLC)1083265020  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA643.86.C3 7aHEA0390202bisacsh04a362.19697/920097122300aThinking Differently about HIV/AIDS :bContributions from Critical Social Science /ced. by Eric Mykhalovskiy, Viviane Namaste. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (372 p.) :b1 b&w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCritical Dispositions -- tOn the Possibility of Being Governed Otherwise -- tTracking Treatment Adherence -- tInstitutional Ethnography as a Critical Research Strategy -- tConversation Analysis and Critical Social Science -- tIndigenous Knowing in HIV Research in Canada -- tEmpirical Case Studies -- tThinking Critically about HIV Prevention for Gay and Bisexual Men -- tUndetectable Optimism -- tA Critical Case-Study Analysis of the Logic and Practices of Prescribing HIV Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP) to At-Risk Adolescents -- tThe Social Relations of Disclosure -- tEpidemiology, the Media, and Vancouver’s Public Health Emergency A Critical Ethnography -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlmost four decades after the scientific discovery of HIV/AIDS, the world continues to grapple with this public health challenge. A successful response requires thinking differently about the epidemic, but what type of thinking can facilitate effective change? Thinking Differently about HIV/AIDS explores the limits of mainstream approaches to the HIV/AIDS epidemic and challenges readers to develop alternate solutions, placing particular emphasis on the value of critical social science perspectives. The contributors investigate traditions of inquiry – governmentality studies, institutional ethnography, Indigenous knowledges, conversation analysis, actor-network theory, critical ethnography, and others – to determine what these perspectives can bring to HIV/AIDS research, policy, and prevention programming. Engaging with various knowledge frameworks, they examine the criminalization of HIV, epidemiological and media constructions of the epidemic, HIV non-disclosure, treatment adherence, and other topics. This book is the first Canadian anthology of critical social science perspectives on HIV/AIDS, demonstrating how and why critical social science is necessary for rethinking research and action required to address the epidemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAIDS (Disease)xResearchzCanada. 0aAIDS (Disease)zCanada. 0aCritical thinkingzCanada. 0aHIV (Viruses). 0aHIV infectionsxResearchzCanada. 0aHIV infectionszCanada. 0aSocial sciencesxResearchzCanada. 0aSocial scienceszCanada. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Diseases / AIDS & HIV.2bisacsh1 aAdam, Barry D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAguinaldo, Jeffrey P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Denielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrench, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaspar, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrace, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuta, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHastings, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc